Description: This item is used as fault reporting text to show that the processing of a beam was aborted due to an inconsistency in the prepared segment, for example:
1.Wrong energy/mode
2.Invalid combination of geometric position requests.
The confirmed value part shows the opcode of the faulty message.
This item is used to indicate when the <FAULT RESET> switch on the front of the TCC should be operated to clear a fault condition.

This item shows that the linear accelerator hardware is ready for operation.  Warm up status can be shown as an inhibit if a problem is detected while validating the energy calibration block settings, or if the calculated dose reference value required to compensate for pressure and temperature falls outside the permitted range, type and resolution.
This item shows the state of the external terminate input from the client interface in the interface cabinet.
This item selects the radiation type to be delivered by the linear accelerator.
This item selects the required energy.
This item sets the total dose per beam for dose channel 1. The returned actual value is the number of MU given per beam.
This item sets the total dose per beam for dose channel 2. The actual value returned is the number of MU given per beam.

This item sets the segment dose per segment for dose channel 1. The actual value returned is the number of MU given per segment. The sum of the segment MU for all segments of a beam must be less than the total MU for that beam - otherwise an abnormal termination results. i683 allows this item to display the generated radiation and read on channel 1.

This item sets the segment dose backup per segment for dose channel 2. The actual value returned is the number of MU given per segment. The segment MU set for channel 2 must exceed the set value for channel 1 to avoid abnormal termination. If no value for channel 2 is entered, the system calculates the value from channel 1 set by adding 10 MU. i684 allows this item to display the generated radiation and read on channel 1.
The value of this item is the beam backup time. If the timer expires, an abnormal termination occurs.

This item specifies the default nominal dose rate to be applied if a zero or invalid entry is made for the prescribed nominal dose rate. Part 1 of this item sets the value. It can be set for each energy.
The set value commands the wedge to move, while the indicated. actual value shows the state of the wedge. It is not valid to enter 0 for the set value.
This item specifies and indicates the type of applicator fitted. It is used for electron treatments only.

This item indicates the state of secondary movements contactor CON-C.
Gate turn-off. Indication that current is still flowing when PFN charge-enable pulse has occurred. HT is inhibited for 1.5 seconds when this fault occurs.

This item displays a value of 0 during a reverse diode overload condition as detected by the HT PSU. The item is for indication only, because the PRF is inhibited for approximately 2 seconds by the HT PSU control circuits.

This item monitors the status of a hardware interlock on the HT PSU control circuits to inhibit further charging pulses if the PFN is already charged

This item indicated that an over temperature fault has occurred in the bending magnet coils. The detectors comprise six thermal cutouts mounted one per bending coil.

This item reads the state of the low pressure switch in the return line to the cooling pump and indicates when cooling water pressure is too low.
It warns that the water pressure is less than 0.7 bar (10 psi) and therefore the low pressure switch has opened. At atmospheric pressure, the switch contacts are normally closed.
In response, the TCC issues a warning (inhibit) only.

This item reads the state of the high pressure switch in the return line to the cooling pump and indicates when cooling water pressure is too high. It warns that the water pressure exceeds 1 bar (15 psi) and therefore the high pressure switch has opened. At atmospheric pressure, the switch contacts are normally closed.
In response, the TCC issues a warning (inhibit) only.
This item warns of a possible impending problem with cooling water pressure.

The sum of the segment MU for all segments of a beam must be less than the total MU for that beam - otherwise an abnormal termination will result.

If no value for channel 2 is entered, the TCC calculates the value from channel 1 set by adding 10 MU.
The value of this item is calculated by FACILITY 2 from the monitored segment MU. Limits can be set to cause termination.

A hardware status bit showing that a 1 MU count has occurred in dosimetry channel 1. The software acknowledges the status bit by writing ACKNOWLEDGE COUNT to the DOS-A PCB. Otherwise a hardware termination occurs.
A hardware status bit showing whether the test link is inserted in dosimetry channel 1. If the test link is inserted, it is not possible to operate in Clinical Mode.
A hardware status bit showing whether the reset is enabled in dosimetry channel 1.

A hardware status bit showing whether a fault exists in any power supply to dosimetry channel 1. The monitored supplies are: +15 V, -15 V, +6.3 V ref, -300 V. +5 V is implicitly checked by accessing the DOS-A PCB.
A hardware status bit showing whether an excess rate fault has occurred in dosimetry channel 1. The hardware excess rate fault is tripped at a dose rate of between 1100 MU/min and 1200 MU/min.
A hardware status bit showing whether the reset is applied in dosimetry channel 1.
A hardware status bit showing whether new settings can be written to dosimetry channel 1.
A hardware status bit showing whether the dummy dose FET in dosimetry channel 1 is On, allowing a dummy dose to be injected for complete sequence test.

A hardware status bit showing whether the dosimetry relay in dosimetry channel 1 is enabled. The relay is disabled by any fault status, and by end of beam on the hardware counters. The relay is re-enabled by a dosimetry reset.
This item shows a dose channel 1 hardware status bit showing if an illegal write has occurred.

This is a process item used to handle the stepping through intermediate PRFs on step changes of PRF and at start of pulsing.
This item is enabled when the Continuously Variable Doserate option is selected and the maximum legacy PRF code (7) is used.
The PRF Factor is an 8 bit value in the range 0-255, and is calculated as follows:
PRF_Factor = 256 x ( Required Doserate / Maximum Doserate ) - 1
This item turns Continually Variable Dose Rate (CVDR) mode on or off.
When set to 0 (zero), C-VDR mode is off, and there are only 7 doserate steps available, relating to 400, 200, 100, 50, 25, 12 and 6 PPS.
If PRF Mode is set to 1 (one), then C-VDR mode is enabled, allowing 256 discrete doserate steps.
